September 30, 1996

PM unhappy with UN Security Council"s failure to censure Israel

from BUSINESS TIMES, The New Straits Times Press (Malaysia) Berhad,
     30 Sep 1996, page 20

PRIME Minister Datuk Seri Mahathir Mohamad yesterday expressed
disappointment with the UN Security Council members for their failure to
censure the Israeli Government led by Mr Benjamin Netanyahu for breaching
the peace agreement between Palestine and Israel.
  "The Security Council members should have taken into account the various
violations committed by the Netanyahu Government such imposing blockades
on Palestine by preventing Palestinian aircraft to land on the Palestinian
airport, preventing Palestinians to commute to work, and building of
Israeli settlements," he told reporters at the Sultan Abdul Aziz
International Airport yesterday.
  "Members of the Security Council failed to accuse Israel of committing
these violations out of fear of being branded as pro-Palestine," Dr
Mahathir said.
  "That is why we had the (UN Security Council's) resolution calling for
the cessation of hostilities, closure of tunnel and resumption of peace
talks.
  "I am attracted to (British Foreign Secretary Malcolm) Rifkind's speech,
where he outlined one-by-one all the violations of treaty committed by
Israel since Netanyahu took office as Israeli Prime Minister."
                              

