BUSINESS TIMES (MALAYSIA) via NewsNet
September 30, 1996

Amcorp sees abundant opportunities for expansion

from BUSINESS TIMES, The New Straits Times Press (Malaysia) Berhad,
     30 Sep 1996, page 5

WITH the Malaysian economy heading for the ninth consecutive year of
strong growth, opportunities are abound for Arab-Malaysian Corp Bhd
(Amcorp) to further enhance its position as a leading provider of
financial, property and infrastructure services, says its chairman Tan Sri
Azman Hashim.
  In his latest annual statement, the chairman says the group will
"entrench our strategy on our financial and property/infrastructure
services expertise to create synergies these two core business areas and
at the same time, seek to develop our interests in other sectors such as
industrial services".
  Reviewing the group's performance, Azman says the group's core business
areas continued to record impressive growth.
  Amcorp's activities in property development have been given a boost when
it acquired about 82.96ha of land for the development of 311 bungalow lots
under the exclusive Kayang Heights development project, which is next to
the Bukit Cerakah Forest Reserve in Shah Alam.
  Amcorp has also successfully concluded conditional mandatory general
offers for shares in two companies. The first being the shares in
Melawangi Sdn Bhd, developer of the prestigious Amcorp Trade Centre in
Petaling Jaya, which is now 100 per cent-owned by Amcorp.
  The other is South Peninsular Industries Bhd, a manufacturing company
listed on the Kuala Lumpur Stock Exchange (KLSE) second board, which is
presently a 51 per cent-owned subsidiary of the group.
  Azman says growth within AMMB Holdings Bhd, which led the financial
services sector of the group, continued to be significant. Among the
developments is the commencement of offshore banking operation in Labuan.
  Elsewhere, Arab-Malaysian Securities Holding Sdn Bhd expanded its
operations to Indonesia when it acquired a 60 per cent stake in Jakarta-
based stockbroking firm, now renamed PT Arab-Malaysian Capital Indonesia.
The group, through a subsidiary company, has also acquired a seat on The
Stock Exchange of Hong Kong Ltd.
  Arab-Malaysian Merchant Bank, which obtained Tier-1 status and the
approval from Bank Negara to open four more branches, has entered into an
asset management joint-venture agreement with Macquarie Bank Ltd of
Australia.
  Closer to home, AMMB Futures Sdn Bhd began operations trading in futures
contracts on the Kuala Lumpur Options and Financial Futures Exchange and
the Malaysia Monetary Exchange. Meanwhile, Arab-Malaysian Finance Bhd and
Arab-Malaysian Bank Bhd has also received approvals from the Central Bank
to open nine and eight new branches respectively.
  Azman says the growth prospect of the Malaysian economy is expected to
create increased loan demand which will provide lending opportunities for
the AMMB Holdings group. Likewise, activities in the capital markets will
remain robust, in line with Government's objective of promoting Kuala
Lumpur as a regional financial hub.
  "Thus, the group is poised to harness further opportunities arising in
the forthcoming year," says the chairman.
  Other significant events include the listing of Powertek Bhd, in which
Arab-Malaysian Development Bhd has a 30 per cent stake, on the main board
of the KLSE. Azman says this is notable as it is the first independent
power producer and first new infrastructure project company to be listed.
  For the year ended March 31 1996, the Amcorp group registered a profit
before tax of RM321.9 million, which shows a growth of 38.6 per cent.
Profits from Amcorp's own activities, comprising financial services and
property construction and development, surged by 79.3 per cent to RM87.7
million.
                               

