BUSINESS TIMES (MALAYSIA) via NewsNet
September 30, 1996

Marina Cove"s RM100m project

from BUSINESS TIMES, The New Straits Times Press (Malaysia) Berhad,
     30 Sep 1996, page 6

By Meera T'Ratnam

MALACCA-bound Marina Cove which will be built on a 35-acre coastal site at
the Kuala Linggi riverine estuary joins the latest string of waterfront
development projects to take off this  year.
  Construction for the RM100 million integrated waterfront property is set
for December this year. The project will be developed by Harvest Rimba
Sdn Bhd, a subsidiary of public listed Harvest Court Industries Bhd.
  The development, which is projected to be completed by 1999 is situated
close to Port Dickson and the new Kuala Lumpur International Airport in
Sepang.
  "We are very pleased and excited to be developing this project in
Malacca given the state's historical ties with the sea. With the
development of Marina Cove, we hope to generate local interest in yatching
and other related activities," director of Harvest Rimba Sdn Bhd, Encik
Abdul Halim Yunus said.
  "The main attractions of the cove lie in its low resident per acre
density, exclusive home designs and its own private marina berthing
facilities," he said, in a statement.
  "These factors, together with pleasant surroundings and world-class
marina facilities make it a high value investment."
  Marina Cove waterfront project, which was launched a few days ago by the
Chief Minister of Malacca Datuk Seri Haji Mohd Zin Abdul Ghani, will
comprise of bungalows, townhouses, apartments, shops, hotel apartments, a
clubhouse with marine facilities and a broadwalk.
  "Marina Cove will have the lowest resident density per acre in the
waterfront marina development segment. We will be developing only 12 units
per acre  compared to the industry average of 40 units per acre," said
Abdul Halim.
  "Because we want own ers and residents to enjoy the privacy and serenity
for their surroundings, we will be developing only 19.25 acres of the
alloted 35 acres of coastal land. The remaining acre is devoted to open
spaces and water ways," he said.
  On the developed area, a Marina Arcade comprising of 10 shoplots and a
16-storey Waterfront Apartel consisting of a 150 unit apartment hotel will
be built.
  On the residential side, Cove Apartments-made up of five different
blocks of either four or five storeys and only 176 apartments, will be
built. The company also plans to offer 80 units  of terraced townhouses
with private berthing facilities as part of its Waterfront Quay Terrace.
  "In other waterfront projects in Malaysia, private berthing facilities
are available only to bungalow owners. Marina Cove has extended this
exclusive facility to our terrace house owners because we want as many
residents as possible to enjoy the pleasure of yachting and boating," he
added.
  Some 20 bungalow lots are expected to be available to owners of
Waterfront Villas.
                               

