<A NAME = "34"></A>Copyright
BUSINESS TIMES (MALAYSIA) via NewsNet
September 30, 1996

MAH to "represent all hotel views"

from BUSINESS TIMES, The New Straits Times Press (Malaysia) Berhad,
     30 Sep 1996, page 3

By Kang Siew Li

MALAYSIA Association of Hotels (MAH) president Mazli Mohamed wants the
211-member body to be truly representative of the entire sector by getting
most, if not all, the nation's hoteliers to join MAH.
  "I don't want the association to be perceived as one that only looks
after the welfare of hotels in Kuala Lumpur just because it is based in
the capital," he told Business Times in Kuala Lumpur.
  Mazli who is also Holiday Inn (hotel operations/development) general
manager, has taken the first step by ensuring the association represents
the views of hotels across the board.
  "Our new management committee members comprise not only four- and five-
star hotels but also three-star operations as well," said Mazli, who has
taken over from Encik Azman Harun whose two-year term ended recently.
  Mazli wants the association to be more vocal in fighting for the
interests of hotels and the industry. MAH is currently seeking to lower
electricity charges which have gone up with the withdrawal of the 10 per
cent discount on electricity tariffs for the hotel sector.
  He said the hotel industry contributes substantially to the country's
total electricity consumption and that the average three- or four-star
hotel (with 200 to 300 rooms) in Kuala Lumpur spends about RM500,000 per
year on electricity.
  Tenaga Nasional Bhd is very aware of this and it has already raised
electricity charges considerably without giving prior notice, he said.
  The association has submitted a memorandum to Energy, Telecommunications
and Posts Minister Datuk Leo Moggie in June to consider its claims but has
yet to receive a response.
  MAH, working together with the Government, is also looking into
ambiguities in sewerage and service charges, the Social Security
Organisation (Socso), the Employees Provident Fund (EPF) and wages.
  "We have compiled these matters in a memorandum which has already been
sent to Deputy Prime Minister and Finance Minister Datuk Seri Anwar
Ibrahim during a pre-budget dialogue session in Ipoh in July," he added.
  Mazli said the hotel industry is presently enjoying a boom, with hotel
occupancy rates at between 70 and 80 per cent.
  "At the end of next year, we'll see tremendous growth in hotels in the
country as the industry gears up to host the Commonwealth Games for the
first time," he explained.
  At present, there are about 55,000 hotel rooms in the country.
  The number is expected to reach 100,000 by the end of next year.
  On whether the hotel market will be saturated then, he says, this
largely "depends on how well we promote our country and how good our
economy will be".
  "Equally important is the location of a hotel. If a hotel is not
properly located, it may suffer with the onset of fierce competition," he
added.
  However, Mazli said one unavoidable problem is the shortage of skilled
workers and service staff.
  "This will inevitably lead to an uncontrolled increase in wages as
hotels fight for more staff to fill positions in their hotels. Each
(hotel) tends to offer more for similar posts," he explained.
  Because the market share for hotels is becoming smaller, Mazli said
hoteliers must now work hand in hand with the authorities to find ways and
means to bring in more visitors into the country.
  "I think we should not rely solely on the Government to bring in more
visitors. I believe hotels have got to do more," he said.
  He added that the association has been supporting the Government in all
its efforts to promote tourism in the country.
  Mazli said MAH is currently working with the Malaysian Association of
Tour and Travel Agents and the Malaysia Tourism Promotion Board in
anticipation of the Asean Tourism Forum which will be held in Kuala Lumpur
in January next year.
  "The event will generate income and create more awareness of Malaysia's
tourism industry," he believes.
  "At the same time, the association is also looking at the meetings,
incentives, conventions and exhibitions (MICE) sector.
  "This is one component of the tourism business that I think will
contribute major exchange earnings to the country in the long run," he
said, adding that business travellers have higher disposable incomes and
their length of stay is longer.
  Mazli said there is a need to build convention centres in Kuala Lumpur,
Penang and Kuantan so that business will be spread out evenly.
  According to him, the construction of the Kuala Lumpur International
Airport (KLIA) in Sepang marks the beginning of a new era, as "the new
airport means more airlines will be coming in, more visitors and more
business for the hotel industry".
                               

Pix: Mazli ... tremendous growth in hotels in the country.

