BUSINESS TIMES (MALAYSIA) via NewsNet
September 30, 1996

Ordinary week but for 2nd board plunge

from BUSINESS TIMES, The New Straits Times Press (Malaysia) Berhad,
     30 Sep 1996, page 11

By Roziana Hamsawi

IT WOULD have been a rather uninteresting week if not for the "sad
incident" which befell  a majority of the second board stocks on Thursday,
leaving punters to shift their attention to cheaper main board stocks.
  Otherwise, the local bourse last week was mildly active on quite a
healthy number of shares traded, making it "generally uninteresting but
definitely not boring" according to one analyst.
  Despite the country's seven months' good trade figures, the market had
started out on a weak note last week, arising from the uncertainties in
the direction of US interest rates. The KLSE Composite Index, on Monday,
lost 4.09 points, closing at 1,126.51 while the second board index rose
1.35 points up to 608.48.
  On Wednesday, shares rose in active trade with strong gains registered
in index-linked stocks. It was an immediate reaction to the US Federal
Open Market Committee's decision to maintain interest rates at the current
level. The Composite Index closed 5.59 points higher at 1,129.31, while
the second board rose 16.62 points to 625.41.
  After a continuous upward movement in the second board index, Thursday
saw it tumble down 24.86 points or 3.98 per cent to 600.55. Although a
correction was expected, the fall on Thursday was due to concerns of
restrictions on second board stocks, imposed by some local stockbroking
firms. The KLCI, however remained steady, losing only half a point to
1,128.81.
  The last day of the week ended fairly mixed with the CI moving up 1.78
points at 1,130.59 while the second board index continued its downward
fall, breaching the 600-psychological level to end the week at 595.58. The
first time the second board index hit the 600 level was the Friday before
when it closed at 607.13.
  Overall last week, a total of some 1.647 billion shares were traded
worth RM14.258 billion compared to 1.781 billion shares worth RM15.006
billion the week before.
  About 914.247 million shares were traded on the main board valued at
RM6.681 billion, while the second board saw a total of 602.420 million
shares done worth RM7.114 billion.
  Analysts said for this week, the market is expected to move sideways,
with speculative main board stocks continuing to attract punters. Interest
in second board stocks, however will not cease, said one analyst.
                               

Copyright 1996 The New Straits Times Press (Malaysia) Berhad



