<A NAME = "36"></A>Copyright
BUSINESS TIMES (MALAYSIA) via NewsNet
September 30, 1996

Chart trend: Bourse set to be choppy with wide fluctuations

from BUSINESS TIMES, The New Straits Times Press (Malaysia) Berhad,
     30 Sep 1996, page 11

By Raymond

ACTIVITY on the Kuala Lumpur Stock Exchange (KLSE) started on Monday with
blue-chips taking a back seat while play resumed among speculative stocks
on the second board.
  Negative trade figures which were reported did not have a significant
impact on the KLSE.
  Volatile trading on Tuesday saw second board stocks trading in an
erratic fashion.
  Stocks on the main board were not doing much either, one way or the
other.
  Heavy speculative buying on Wednesday pushed prices of small capital
stocks upwards.
  The overall market sentiment also improved with a new batch of stocks
which came into play.
  The volatile movement of second board stocks continued on Thursday, only
this time round, they were hammered by aggressive selling.
  The bearish situation was, however, cushioned by firm support for
selective main board stocks which registered good gains.
  Mixed trading was the order of the day on Friday. Market sentiment was
pulled down by cautious selling on second board stocks, while only the
situational issues on the main board were giving supportive play in the
market.
  For the week, second board stocks were again in the limelight for the
right and wrong reasons.
  The much expected correction came in to cool off the over speculation
which has taken the second board stocks to record highs.
  Market players who were caught on the high side would be licking their
wounds, but for medium- term investors, this correction is healthy.
  Sentiment wise, the KLSE is expected to be choppy with wild fluctuations
to remain a feature among second board stocks.
  The market minus the very speculative second board stocks is still
attractive in value terms and interest may just shift to main baord
counters.
  In the past couple of weeks, there has been a slow uptrend which has not
caught too much attention among main board counters.
  This gradual momentum has not produced anything spectacular but with
patience there is a high potential for lagging stocks to bring in the
rewards.
  On the technical front our short-term Timing Device has been on the
downtrend for the past eight trading sessions and currently the falling
pace has been steadily reduced in the past four sessions.
  It is quite possible that this short-term market barometer which is now
standing at -56.4 points, is preparing itself for a trend reversal
sometime this week.
  The first supporting level is at -119.2 points, failing which, it is
expected to have the second support at around the -300 point level.
  Our O/O Indicator has continued to go up but at a lesser pace.
  Until this rising market barometer is arrested, we will continue to
remain bullish and treat corrections such as the one we are now seeing as
a technical pullback, which are necessary for any rally in the market.
  Currently, breaking out of the overhead resistance at zero is vital to
the continuation of the bullish trend we are seeing.
  Failure to do so can lead to our market heading for a new serious
correction.BT O/O INDICATOR
-20.6 (up 16.5)

TIMING INDEX
Mon  +51.5
Tue   -7.1
Wed  -25.5
Thu  -43.3
Fri  +56.4
                               

Copyright 1996 The New Straits Times Press (Malaysia) Berhad



