<A NAME = "41"></A>Copyright
BUSINESS TIMES (MALAYSIA) via NewsNet
September 30, 1996

Rates expected to close firmer this week

from BUSINESS TIMES, The New Straits Times Press (Malaysia) Berhad,
     30 Sep 1996, page 14

By Bank Bumiputra Treasury Division

INTERBANK money rates closed firmer as players borrowed the short- to
medium-term money for the settlement of the new bonds to be issued today.
  Shorter-end money rates rose higher while the longer-end closed steady
as covering activities were mostly centered on the short to medium tenors.
The highlight of the week was the tender result of the new bonds issue
which was announced on Friday afternoon.
  The 7-year MGS 2/96 coupon, fixed at 6.586 per cent, rallied after the
result to a high of RM100.60 as short covering activities took place. It
settled at RM100.33/35 in active trading.
  Even though the market was still flush with excess liquidity, term money
rates were pushed up in anticipation of a tighter market next week as
there will be an outflow of RM2.0 billion being payment for the new bonds
issue.
  The benchmark one, three and six months closed higher at 7.25/30 per
cent, 7.30/35 per cent and 7.33/35 per cent respectively.
  While one, two and three weeks money closed above 7.00 per cent as
dealers did not want to be caught short next week.
  The new MGS 2/96 bonds showed a big jump as the yield was depressed to
as low as 6.48 per cent after the announcement compared to 6.60/58 per
cent when it was traded in the grey market. It however retraced to close
the week at a 6.53 per cent yield (price RM100.33/35).
  There was no Bank Negara bills issue during the week forcing some banks
who were short on their liquid assets requirement to buy up Bank Negara
bills in the secondary market.
  As a result the band 4 (68 to 91 days) Bank Negara Bills dropped to
6.65/63 per cent at closing compared to the last tender result average
which was at 6.728 per cent.
  For this week, we expect rates to tighten temporarily due to the payment
of the RM2.0 billion for the new bonds.
                               

Copyright 1996 The New Straits Times Press (Malaysia) Berhad



