<A NAME = "43"></A>Copyright
BUSINESS TIMES (MALAYSIA) via NewsNet
September 30, 1996

Money talk: Investors surprised by Fed decision

from BUSINESS TIMES, The New Straits Times Press (Malaysia) Berhad,
     30 Sep 1996, page 14

By Bank of America Treasury Division

EARLIER last week, speculation of whether the US Federal Reserve will
increase interest rates during the FOMC meeting had preoccupied the
foreign exchange market.
  However, the market was caught by surprise with the Fed's decision to
leave interest rates unchanged, prompting fresh concerns about rising
inflation. The FOMC voted against raising short-term rates, even though a
majority of analysts had predicted a modest 25 basis points increase.
  Currency investors that had banked on a rate increase sold the US dollar
from 1.5140 to 1.50  marks, with strong support seen intact at 1.4980.
Some dealers blamed politics for delaying a much-needed interest rate
increase, with the pressure of Presidential and Congressional elections in
November.
  By the end of the week, the market witnessed a steady bid interest on
the US dollar after a surprising Swiss interest rate cut. Switzerland cut
its discount rate to an 18-year low of 1 per cent from 1.5 per cent and
investors fled the Swiss franc and the mark . Investors appear to have
forgotten their dissapointment with the Fed's decision to keep interest
rates untouched. The market is also expecting lower interest rates in
Germany in the coming months. The market has also turned a blind eye to
the dissolution of the Japanese Parliament's Lower House.  The market
closed at 1.5240 amd 110.70 against the mark and the yen respectively.
  As for next week, the market is vulnerable to all US indicators in the
run-up to the key non-farm payroll on Friday. Some analysts believe that
the US asset markets are currently hyper-sensitive to all kinds of rates
and so the US dollar could be on its guard. Others express concern that
the US dollar is gaining its strength mainly from external factors. The US
dollar will require fresh internal incentives/factors to rise above its
current key resistance level of 1.5250 marks.
  As for the local unit, the ringgit fell to the 2.51 level on fresh US
dollar demand ahead of the month-end requirements from commercials and
also due to heavy stop losses orders being triggered as the market
approaches the 2.51 level. The market is expected to be traded between
2.5050 and  2.5125 for next week.
  As for the Asian currencies, we expect the Singapore dollar/ringgit  to
trade between the 1.7750 and 1.7880 range and  the yen/ringgit between
2.2500 to 2.2800.
  (While every effort has been taken to ensure accuracy, no liability is
assumed on our part for error of facts and opinions.)
                               

Copyright 1996 The New Straits Times Press (Malaysia) Berhad



