VIETNAM: $1bn for flat steel mill

from BUSINESS VIETNAM, November 1, 1996

Hanoi:

Vietnam's attempts to aggressively recruit foreign companies to build
steel mills within its borders are about to pay off in a big way.
Korea's Posco and Daewoo are finalising plans to build Vietnam first
flat-product steel mill, which could cost as much as $1 billion.

"We are discussing this project with Daewoo and VSG," Sujin Oh,
Posco's chief representative in Hanoi said.  "We have finished the
pre-feasibility study."

The large infrastructual needs expected to be associated with the
project are causing headaches in determining its location.  At
least three sites are under consideration, two in central Vietnam
and one in the north.  The Vietnamese are again pushing for Duang
Quat as a steel mill fits in well with their ideas of
industrialising central Vietnam.  Costs for infrastructure alone,
including a deep-see port that could accommodate ships of at least
40,000 dead-weight tonnes and adequate electricity and roads, are
likely to be about US$200 million.

"We assume the Vietnamese government will provide the
infrastructure," he said.  The Vietnamese are assuming that the
foreigners will pay for it.

Four joint ventures between Vietnam Steel Corporation and foreign
partners have come on line within the last 18 months with a total
capacity of more than 700,000 tonnes.  This is still short of
Daewoo's annual projections for Vietnam of 3 million tons by 2000.

All of these mills are producing construction steel, which is used
primarily for reinforcing buildings.

Vietnam at present has no mills producing flat steel, which is used
in products such as cars, refrigerators and washing machines.  The
Korean flat steel mill will be a welcome part of the national
strategy that Vietnam is encouraging in its shift to heavy
manufacturing.

