BURMA: $7 billion despite pressure

from BUSINESS VIETNAM, November 1, 1996

Rangoon:

The generals in Burma have reason to feel optimistic.  Despite
increasing pressure for foreigners to disinvest and continuing
American calls for sanctions, total approved investment in Burma
should reach $7 billion by year's end.  All is from the private
sector with oil and gas attracting the most investment with 25
projects worth $1.44 billion.

Since 1988 when SLORC took over the government no loans had been
forthcoming from international financial institutions such as the
World Bank (WB), the International Monetary Fund (IMF) and Asian
Development Bank (ADB).

The lack of foreign aid and soft loans does restrict development,
says David Abel, the country's Minister for Economic Development.
But he still believes that private investment will continue to
blossom with another $1.5 billion committed by March 1997.

Whereas Abel believes that Burma, which is still a member of the
governing bodies of the WB, ADB and IMF, faces only political
obstacles rather than "technical" ones for the resumption of loans.
 An ADB official said the inadequacy of economic reforms in Burma
and the government's foreign exchange policy were the main
stumbling blocks.

American companies remain the leading investors in Burma with more
than $250m committed so far on 15 projects.  Some 20 countries have
so far invested $4.13 billion in 176 projects, with two European
nations among the top three investors.

Britain tops the list with $1.003 billion invested, followed by
Singapore ($896 million) and France ($465 million).

