BUSINESS VIETNAM via NewsNet
November 1, 1996

VIETNAM: Hanoi admits foreigners are sceptical

from BUSINESS VIETNAM, November 1, 1996

Hanoi:

In a somewhat refreshing comment, a high level official in Vietnam's
Ministry of Planning and Investment (MPI), vice-minister Nguyen
Nhac, has admitted that despite a decade of opening up, foreign
investors are still sceptical of the government's policies.

This month should see the amendment for the third time of Vietnam's
Foreign Investment Law.  It is supposed to focus on simplification
of post-licence procedures, such as land use permits, construction
permits and taxation, and other challenges which foreign investors
are encountering that, presumably, covers things such as the state
theft of 40 containers of mining equipment from Westralian Sands
earlier this year.

Under the revamped investment law investors will get permits for
land use and construction in one month.  The government has
facilitated licence procedures since the merger of a licensing body
(State Committee for Cooperation and Investment) and a planning
agency (State Planning Committee) last year creating a theoretical
one-stop service at the Ministry of Planning and Investment (MPI).

But investors are still struggling in some areas of investment and
in some parts of the country, Nhac said.  "In some areas MPI works,
but in others there are still problems.  That's why we're
determined to perfect our legal framework and improve the
environment including infrastructure.  In certain areas, investment
is falling, such as in real estate and office/hotel projects.  But
we see a good trend: over 80% of the projects are manufacturing
industries, which is in line with our needs."

MPI is considering more incentives or facilities for industrial
estate development.  "We try to provide facilities, the lowest land
rents of fees, fewer taxes and longer tax exemptions," he said.

What Nhac would do well to consider is a concerted effort to
prevent foreign investors from being ripped off at the slightest
excuse.  Over-charging and corruption is one thing.  That can be
managed.  But orchestrated state theft is quite another.  There is
far too much of both at a time when Vietnam is facing serious regional
competition for the investment dollar.

