BUSINESS VIETNAM via NewsNet
November 1, 1996

VIETNAM: What's in a road ?

from BUSINESS VIETNAM, November 1, 1996

Hanoi:

Laos and Vietnam are like two lovers sleeping together, but if they are
to grow together the roads linking them must be expanded and
upgraded.  The Lao's want the access to Vietnam's deep water ports that
will wean them away from expensive road transport and Bangkok.  The
Vietnamese are looking for tourist and trade links across Laos to
Thailand.  A number of options have been put forward, some by Laos,
others by Vietnam.  There is no doubt as to the benefits should road
links between Laos and Vietnam improve.

Route 8 which links Paksane with Vinh in Vietnam is the road most
favoured by the Lao's.  It is the shortest route from Thailand to
Vietnam, as well as from Vientiane to Vietnam.  The 260 kms of the road
that
is in Vietnam is in reasonable condition while much of the Laotian part
is barely usable over mountainous, winding terrain.  The road also
complements the continuing construction of Nam Theun 2 and Nam
Theun Hinboon hydro power plants.  Route 9 connects Mukdahan with
Savannakhet in Laos and Vietnam's central port town of Da Nang, some 500
kms away.  Again, in Vietnam it is in fairly good shape while in Laos it
is in bad need of repair.  There are plans, perhaps dreams would be
a better description, to revamp an old railway that runs parallel
to Route 9.

Both routes are seen as new avenues for the free flow of goods
between industrial northeastern Thailand and Vietnam.  Developing them
is a priority project for the Asian Development Bank, which is the
main advocate of a sub-regional cooperation scheme for six
countries sharing the Mekong River: China, Vietnam, Laos, Burma,
Thailand and Cambodia.

Since Vietnam is pressing ahead towards industrialisation or
semi-industrialisation by the year 2000 its leaders are aiming for
social, political as well as economic results by promoting direct
foreign investment in what is the poorest part of the country.
Laos, for its part, is serious about economic development and
raising the people's standard of living.  By 2000 it wants to see
its per capita income up to $500 a year and to introduce
electricity to at least half of Savannakhet province.  It is hoping
that renovating Routes 8 and 9 will give the province the magical
impetus.

The economic boast will, of course, come from he hundreds of
millions of dollars needed for the upgrade.  Its not just the roads
that require money.  Besides upgrading and reconstructing roads,
software issues like customs and immigration procedures also have
to be worked out.  The ADB is reported to be committed to financial
assistance, but disbursement will take time.  But once it does
start to roll out its millions there will be plenty all round for
foreign expertise and investment in the tourist infrastructure
associated with the two projects.

