VIETNAM: Hold that lease

from BUSINESS VIETNAM, November 1, 1996

Saigon:

Imagine that you're found your ideal office on home in Vietnam and the
lease is awaiting signature.  Before signing it would be wise to
consider the hidden extras.  An apparent `good deal' could be a
disaster in the making.

Depending on whether one is in the north or the south, measurement
can very greatly.  In the north, most buildings are let on a nett
internal area basis.  In the south, most projects are offered on a
gross area basis which means that tenants are charged for all the
common areas.  These could occupy as much as 20% of the floor area.

Rents are usually quoted nett of taxes and service charges, the
latter ranging from $3 to $8 psm.  When paying rent, expect also to
pay the 20% tax that is levied on the landlord's income.  That
brings the psm cost to 110% of rental.  Car parks are seldom
included in a rental.  They could cost an extra $100 psm per month.
 Even parking a bicycle may not be free.  Where daytime
air-conditioning costs may be included in the service costs, night
time or holiday air-conditioning will be extra.  The ideal building
should have a separate electricity meter for every tenant.

Once the extras have been understood and factored into the rental,
the lease can be signed.  Then one is faced with fit-out costs of
$250 psm for average quality to up to $1,000 psm for a quality that
approximates the best that Hongkong would have to offer.

It is vital that a tenant has clear understanding of what be is
getting.  In Vietnam, the `fair' part of a deal is usually found on the
side of the Vietnamese.

Copyright 1996 Business Vietnam




