<A NAME = "19"></A>Copyright
CHINA BUSINESS INFORMATION NETWORK via NewsNet
September 25, 1996

China: High-tech code system developed to combat fake goods

from CHINA BUSINESS INFORMATION NETWORK (CBnet), Sep. 25, 1996

A high-tech system that uses secret codes to combat fake goods in China
is to go national after a successful trial operation.

The system, invented by Chinese experts, uses a telephone network and
electronic codes to identify genuine articles. A national work
conference held in Haikou of Hainan Province to discuss the system has
been told it is to be spread nationwide after been proved successful.

Its trial operation in parts of the country since January this year
received positive response from users.

China Anti-Fakes Association is entrusted by the State Bureau of
Technical Supervision to popularize it throughout the country.

Hainan Tenglong Anti-Fake Technology Company, which is based in Haikou,
capital of Hainan in South China, is responsible for implementing the
project.

The system, based on computerized data banks and the national
computerized telephone information retrieval network, will provide
manufacturers of quality products with special data codes and secret
codes.

Commodity dealers or buyers can check up the goods they have purchased
by telephone, after tearing off the cover on the codes.

Since it is a hi-tech system, it is impossible for anyone to produce
fake codes, according to experts.

The Hainan-based company has invested 40 million yuan ($4.8 million) to
set up a data bank capable of holding 50 billion different electronic
codes. Terminals will be built in major cities across the country.

Some experts say the network will help protect quality and brand-famed
products in the country.

Copyright 1996 China Business Information Network




