Shanghai to import German escalators for Metro Line No. 2

from CHINA BUSINESS INFORMATION NETWORK (CBnet), Sep. 25, 1996

Shanghai Metro Corp and a German firm have agreed to import 120
escalators for the first phase of the city's Metro Line No 2, which is
scheduled to be completed in 1999.

The 120 computer-controlled heavy-duty escalators cost 24.5 million
Deutsche marks ($16 million) and will be designed and manufactured by
Otis Escalator Factory in Stadthagen, Germany.

These escalators will be installed by Shanghai Otis Elevator Corp in 10
subway stations -- four West Shanghai and six in Pudong (East
Shanghai), said an official from the company.

The 3-year-old Shanghai Otis has installed numerous state-of-the-art,
computer-controlled elevators in major projects throughout Shanghai,
including the Oriental Pearl TV Tower.

The escalators for the Metro project will begin arriving in April, the
official said.

Germany will also provide four escalators for the extension of Metro
Line No 1 from Jinjiang Amusement Park to Xinzhuang.

The extension will open at the end of the year, said Chen Mingtu, chief
of the Foreign Economic Division under Shanghai Metro Co.

This is the second project by Otis for Shanghai metros, the Otis
official said, adding that Otis installed 48 heavy-duty escalators for
Metro Line No 1.

Chen said the metro company will soon sign a contract with the United
States to import subway ticket machines worth $24 million. The machines
will be installed on Metro Lines No 1 and No 2.

The city borrowed $50 million from the United States Government to
import subway ticket machines, signal and anti-fire systems.

The city also will import 210 carriages. Most will be for the first
phase of the second subway, and 16 will be used on Metro Line No 1 to
increase the frequency of train trips from every seven minutes to every
five minutes.

