China: Ministry to help upgrade machine plants in northeast China

from CHINA BUSINESS INFORMATION NETWORK (CBnet), Sep. 25, 1996

China's Ministry of Machinery plans to finance the technological
upgrading projects of major machine-building plants in northeast of the
country.

The aim is to boost the growth of an important sector that employs a
quarter of all the area's workers.

The companies to receive government assistance will include
manufacturers of power generation, transformers and transmission
facilities, lathe-builders and suppliers of important fittings and
parts in the bearing industry.

The funding will also be granted to manufacturers of light and heavy
automotives, according to Deputy Minister Sun Changji, who was recently
interviewed by reporter in Liaoning coastal city Dalian.

According to the official, 104 such projects have been approved by the
ministry, involving a total investment of 5.3 billion yuan ($630
million).

The northeastern region normally covers Heilongjiang, Jilin and
Liaoning, as well as the eastern part of Inner Mongolia Autonomous
Region. The area is an old industrial base of the country.

The machinery industry makes up 25.73 percent of the region's total
industrial production value.

The ministry has urged the machinery sector in the northeast to carry
out managerial reforms to revive the old industrial base.

