<A NAME = "33"></A>Copyright
CHINA BUSINESS INFORMATION NETWORK via NewsNet
September 25, 1996

China: 50 reporters granted awards for fighting copyright piracy

from CHINA BUSINESS INFORMATION NETWORK (CBnet), Sep. 25, 1996

China's State Copyright Administration yesterday rewarded 50 reporters
who have helped fight copyright piracy over the past few years.

The reporters work for Xinhua News Agency, "The People's Daily", China
Central Television, and many other news organizations throughout the
country.

"Mass media is playing a major role in promoting people's awareness of
copyright protection," said Yu Youxian, director of the administration.

He said that the Chinese media has published tens of thousands of
stories to demonstrate the significance of copyright protection and
spread information in this regard.

Many people reported copyright cases to the authorities after reading
newspapers, according to Shen Rengan, deputy director of the
administration. He added that it was unusual for a country to mobilize
all its public sectors, including the media, to engage in the fight
against copyright piracy.

Yu Youxian explained that the improvement of people's legal sense by
making use of the media has become a basic guarantee to implement the
copyright law.

The prize-winning stories themselves are a showcase that China has
achieved great progress in protecting copyright, he noted.

He cited some articles, including one describing how farmers become
familiar with the copyright law, one about the Walt Disney's case in
Beijing, and another on copyright protection in a fast food restaurant.

Some reporters lashed the US for its unfair charge that China violated
foreign copyrights. One journalist even told a story about a senior
Chinese copyright official whose works were pirated in the US without
authorization.

Copyright 1996 China Business Information Network




