CHINA BUSINESS INFORMATION NETWORK via NewsNet
September 25, 1996

China: Shanxi plans to harness half of its soil erosion by year 2000

from CHINA BUSINESS INFORMATION NETWORK (CBnet), Sep. 25, 1996

North China's Shanxi Province plans to harness 50 per cent of its soil
erosion area by the year 2000.

Thanks to years of efforts to harness the Loess Plateau, Shanxi has so
far contained 51 million mu (3.06 million hectares), or 32 per cent of
its total eroded area.

Shanxi, located near the middle reaches of the Yellow River, occupies a
large part of the Loess Plateau. Soil erosion area accounts for 70 per
cent of its total 156,000 square kilometer of ground.

In the late 1970s, the annual amount of sand washed into the Yellow
River stood at 366 million tons -- one-fourth of the river's total.

A large-scale campaign to harness the Loess Plateau first began in the
1980s. Over the following several years, 350,000 local rural households
participated in the drive.

By planting grass, trees and crops, and building dams and terraced
farmland, the residents revived hundreds of thousands of barren
gullies.

Meanwhile, the central government and the Shanxi provincial government
also worked to prevent the spread of erosion in the Loess Plateau.

The central government has invested 75 million yuan to tackle erosion
of the banks of the Sanchuan River and Yongding River, two large rivers
on the plateau. Eroded areas which have been controlled there account
for 40 percent of the total drainage area of the two rivers.

A total of 150 million yuan ($18 million) has been used in harnessing
the upper reaches of the Fenhe River, the second largest tributary of
the Yellow River.

Erosion-harnessing projects were carried out on an area of 1.95 million
mu (117,000 hectares) there. In the region, grain output increased by
50 percent, farmers' income rose two-fold, and the volume of sand which
washed into reservoirs was reduced by 49 per cent.

Copyright 1996 China Business Information Network




