September 25, 1996

China: Hebei focuses on airport development

from CHINA BUSINESS INFORMATION NETWORK (CBnet), Sep. 25, 1996

North China's Hubei Province is embracing a rapid developing aviation
industry, according to a report from Shijiazhuang, the provincial
capital.

Until recently the province saw a slow development in aviation
transport, only starting its first civilian flight in 1984.

But since last year the province has stepped up development of air
travel with the opening of Shijiazhuang Airport. The airport is listed
as one of the alternative airports for Beijing Capital International
Airport.

According to provincial aviation officials, Hebei has opened 17
domestic air routes linking the province with 19 major Chinese cities,
and also an air route to Hong Kong.

By the end of October, Shijiazhuang Airport will open four more
domestic air routes to Kunming, Nanjing, Xiamen and Qingdao, and
chartered flights to Russia are expected to begin later this year.

Situated not far from Beijing and Tianjin, two largest cities in the
country, Hebei is one of the major agriculture production bases and
rich in mineral and tourism resources.

By the end of this century, Hubei will transform Shijiazhuang Airport
into an international airport and build or expand four other major
airports in the province.

Copyright 1996 China Business Information Network




